  volume    =  100,
  number    =  1,
  pages     = "64--119",
  abstract  = "The embryonic cell lineage of Caenorhabditis elegans has been
               traced from zygote to newly hatched larva, with the result that
               the entire cell lineage of this organism is now known. During
               embryogenesis 671 cells are generated; in the hermaphrodite 113
               of these (in the male 111) undergo programmed death and the
               remainder either differentiate terminally or become postembryonic
               blast cells. The embryonic lineage is highly invariant, as are
               the fates of the cells to which it gives rise. In spite of the
               fixed relationship between cell ancestry and cell fate, the
               correlation between them lacks much obvious pattern. Thus,
               although most neurons arise from the embryonic ectoderm, some are
               produced by the mesoderm and a few are sisters to muscles; again,
               lineal boundaries do not necessarily coincide with functional
               boundaries. Nevertheless, cell ablation experiments (as well as
               previous cell isolation experiments) demonstrate substantial cell
               autonomy in at least some sections of embryogenesis. We conclude
               that the cell lineage itself, complex as it is, plays an
               important role in determining cell fate. We discuss the origin of
               the repeat units (partial segments) in the body wall, the
               generation of the various orders of symmetry, the analysis of the
               lineage in terms of sublineages, and evolutionary implications.",
