  journal   = "PLoS Genet.",
  publisher = "Public Library of Science (PLoS)",
  volume    =  10,
  number    =  7,
  pages     = "e1004498",
  abstract  = "Interruptions of microsatellite sequences impact genome evolution
               and can alter disease manifestation. However, human polymorphism
               levels at interrupted microsatellites (iMSs) are not known at a
               genome-wide scale, and the pathways for gaining interruptions are
               poorly understood. Using the 1000 Genomes Phase-1 variant call
               set, we interrogated mono-, di-, tri-, and tetranucleotide
