  journal  = "Science",
  volume   =  350,
  number   =  6263,
  pages    = "928--932",
  abstract = "The DNA-binding protein PRDM9 has a critical role in specifying
              meiotic recombination hotspots in mice and apes, but it appears to
              be absent from other vertebrate species, including birds. To study
              the evolution and determinants of recombination in species lacking
              the gene that encodes PRDM9, we inferred fine-scale genetic maps
              from population resequencing data for two bird species: the zebra
              finch, Taeniopygia guttata, and the long-tailed finch, Poephila
              acuticauda. We found that both species have recombination
              hotspots, which are enriched near functional genomic elements.
              Unlike in mice and apes, most hotspots are shared between the two
              species, and their conservation seems to extend over tens of
              millions of years. These observations suggest that in the absence
              of PRDM9, recombination targets functional features that both
              enable access to the genome and constrain its evolution.",
