              G and Niederhuber, John E",
  journal  = "Nat. Commun.",
  volume   =  7,
  pages    =  10486,
  abstract = "Germline mutations are the source of evolution and contribute
              substantially to many health-related processes. Here we use
              whole-genome deep sequencing data from 693 parents-offspring trios
              to examine the de novo point mutations (DNMs) in the offspring.
              Our estimate for the mutation rate per base pair per generation is
              1.05 × 10(-8), well within the range of previous studies. We show
              that maternal age has a small but significant correlation with the
              total number of DNMs in the offspring after controlling for
              paternal age (0.51 additional mutations per year, 95\% CI: 0.29,
              0.73), which was not detectable in the smaller and younger
              parental cohorts of earlier studies. Furthermore, while the total
              number of DNMs increases at a constant rate for paternal age, the
              contribution from the mother increases at an accelerated rate with
              age.These observations have implications related to the incidence
              of de novo mutations relating to maternal age.",
